%N A395590 Primes p such that Mordell's equation y^2 = x^3 - p^3 has at least 1 integral solutions with x > p.
%H A395590 Zhining Yang, <a href="/A395590/b395590.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..118</a>
%H A395590 XiaoYang Zhang, <a href="https://www.zhihu.com/question/2043820485973168194">Within the range of P < 10^5, which primes P yield non-trivial solutions (x ≠ P) to the Modular equation y^2 = x^3 - P^3?</a> (in Chinese).
%e A395590     P [x,y]
%e A395590 --------------------
%e A395590     7 [8,13]
%e A395590     7 [14,49]
%e A395590     7 [28,147]
%e A395590     7 [154,1911]
%e A395590    11 [443,9324]
%e A395590    23 [71,588]
%e A395590    31 [155,1922]
%e A395590    47 [74,549]
%e A395590    61 [793,22326]
